Introduction The objective of this project is to develop a Python-based Bank Account Simulator that allows users to manage banking operations through a command-line interface. The project aims to solve the problem of basic financial record-keeping by providing a practical tool for adding members, depositing and withdrawing funds, and querying balances. This application demonstrates the use of advanced Python concepts in a real-world scenario.
Technologies Used
• Programming Language: Python.
• Data Structures: Dictionaries (used to store account information as key-value pairs).
• Concepts: Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) and Exception Handling.
• Platform: Command-line interface (CLI).
Implementation Details The software is designed using a class-based structure for modularity.
• Kullanici Class: This class serves as the core of the application, managing a dictionary called hesaplar to store customer data.
• Registration Functions: The uye_ekle and uye_sil functions manage the registration and removal of users from the system.
• Transaction Functions: The para_yatir and para_cek methods handle financial transactions, ensuring that balances are updated correctly.
• Query Function: The bakiye_sorgula function allows users to view the current status of their accounts.
• Main Menu: A loop-driven interface called ana_menu provides a user-friendly way to interact with the system.
Challenges & Solutions
• Challenge: Handling invalid user input, such as entering text where a number is expected, which could cause the program to crash.
• Solution: We implemented try-except blocks to catch ValueError exceptions during data entry, ensuring the program provides a warning and continues running instead of terminating unexpectedly.
Conclusion & Future Work This project successfully implements the fundamental requirements of a bank simulation tool. We gained valuable experience in team collaboration and Python programming.
• Future Work: Potential improvements include adding a persistent database (like SQLite) to save data after the program closes and developing a graphical user interface (GUI) for better accessibility.
 
